Let's see.

250
00:09:09,710 --> 00:09:12,820
So if I were to draw a figure,
what I would like to do

251
00:09:12,820 --> 00:09:16,680
is make sure that the
eye level of the figure

252
00:09:16,679 --> 00:09:19,789
is approximately at
the horizon line.

253
00:09:19,789 --> 00:09:23,746
So I would put that
figure in just about here.

254
00:09:23,746 --> 00:09:26,329
SPEAKER 1: And what if you put
a figure more in the foreground

255
00:09:26,330 --> 00:09:27,413
or more in the background?

256
00:09:27,413 --> 00:09:29,870
SPEAKER 2: So if I put
a figure that was more

257
00:09:29,870 --> 00:09:33,870
in the foreground, I would
still want their eye level

258
00:09:33,870 --> 00:09:36,750
to be at that
imaginary horizon line.

259
00:09:36,750 --> 00:09:38,792
But of course, now
they would be larger.

260
00:09:38,792 --> 00:09:39,500
SPEAKER 1: Right.

261
00:09:39,500 --> 00:09:42,039
So I think this is the part
that's counter-intuitive.

262
00:09:42,039 --> 00:09:44,659
The heads are on the
same level, and it's

263
00:09:44,659 --> 00:09:47,057
the feet that are
on different levels.

264
00:09:47,057 --> 00:09:48,389
SPEAKER 2: That's exactly right.

265
00:09:48,389 --> 00:09:53,279
And Alberti also said that that
eye level, that horizon line

266
00:09:53,279 --> 00:09:56,509
would ideally also be
the viewer's eye level

267
00:09:56,509 --> 00:09:59,317
so that the perspective
would really work perfectly.

268
00:09:59,317 --> 00:09:59,899
SPEAKER 1: OK.

269
00:09:59,899 --> 00:10:02,549
So we have orthogonals,
the diagonal lines

270
00:10:02,549 --> 00:10:04,740
that meet at the
vanishing point.

271
00:10:04,740 --> 00:10:10,019
We know the vanishing point is
a point on the horizon line,

272
00:10:10,019 --> 00:10:13,500
and we understand how these
correspond to the viewer

273
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:15,230
and to creating an
illusion of space.

